    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>127900</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><orig>ωνα</orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Intraduisible.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Intraducibile.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمة بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>From other monumental inscriptions, we can only very cautiously suggest either the ending of a personal name in <foreign xml:lang="grc">-ων</foreign> 
                   or of a participle with a meaning such as 'being priest' or 'accomplishing the <foreign rend="italic">telesphoria</foreign>', both at the nominative. 
                   As for the alpha, there are so many possibilities that they do not deserve to be mentioned.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
